WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.700
RoPE groups hidden dimensions into pairs. Each pair behaves like a 2D clock whose phase records position.

00:05.700 --> 00:11.800
Rotating the query at position m and key at position n makes their dot product depend on the relative offset n minus m.

00:11.800 --> 00:18.400
Many rotation frequencies form a positional fingerprint: slow clocks retain long-range phase, while fast clocks distinguish nearby positions.

00:18.400 --> 00:23.600
Real RoPE uses block-diagonal rotations across many dimensions. The circles here are only 2D explanatory toys.

00:23.600 --> 00:31.333
The authors report gains over tested positional alternatives. Shifting both positions equally leaves n minus m, and the relative score, unchanged.
